***  PHP syntax  ***

PHP syntax = the rules that define how PHP code must be written.

Examples:
<?php
// 1. Statements end with semicolon ;
echo "Hello";

// 2. Variables start with $
$name = "John";

// 3. Case sensitivity
$var = 5;  // different from $Var

// 4. Keywords not case sensitive
ECHO "hi"; // works but not recommended

// 5. Comments
// Single line
# Single line
/* Multi line */
?>

Think of it as: PHP grammar - the correct way to write PHP code so the computer understands it.

***  PHP tags  ***

PHP tags = the markers that tell the server "this is PHP code, process it":

Example:
<?php // Opening tag - start PHP

// PHP code goes here

?> // Closing tag - end PHP (optional)

Types:
1. Standard tag: <?php ... ?>
2. Short tag: <? ... ?> (not recommended, may not be supported)
3. ASP tag: <% ... %> (deprecated)
4. Script tag: <script language="php"> ... </script> (not commonly used)

Key rules:
Opening tag <?php is mandatory
Closing tag ?> is optional
If file is only PHP, omit closing tag
Everything outside tags is treated as HTML
